PART 7: COHOMOLOGICAL INTERPRETATION — IS THE VITALI ATOM A COBOUNDARY?
======================================================================

Is delta_H determined by c7 threading through all 4 subset vertices?
  Example 1: c7_A=9, c7_B=8, through_all_A=9, through_all_B=8
    (All 7-cycles pass through all 4 subset vertices trivially: n=7)
  Example 2: c7_A=8, c7_B=9, through_all_A=8, through_all_B=9
    (All 7-cycles pass through all 4 subset vertices trivially: n=7)
  Example 3: c7_A=8, c7_B=9, through_all_A=8, through_all_B=9
    (All 7-cycles pass through all 4 subset vertices trivially: n=7)
  Example 4: c7_A=15, c7_B=14, through_all_A=15, through_all_B=14
    (All 7-cycles pass through all 4 subset vertices trivially: n=7)
  Example 5: c7_A=15, c7_B=14, through_all_A=15, through_all_B=14
    (All 7-cycles pass through all 4 subset vertices trivially: n=7)

  Key insight: since every 7-cycle uses all 7 vertices,
  the reversal changes a 7-cycle iff it uses an ODD number of internal arcs.
  (An arc from subset vertex i to subset vertex j is reversed; if the cycle
   uses an even number of such arcs, the reversal cancels out.)

  Counting 7-cycles by number of INTERNAL arcs used:

  Example 1 (dH=-2): 9 total 7-cycles
    2 internal arcs: 6 cycles
    3 internal arcs: 3 cycles
  After reversal: 8 total 7-cycles
    2 internal arcs: 6 cycles
    3 internal arcs: 2 cycles

  Example 2 (dH=2): 8 total 7-cycles
    2 internal arcs: 6 cycles
    3 internal arcs: 2 cycles
  After reversal: 9 total 7-cycles
    2 internal arcs: 6 cycles
    3 internal arcs: 3 cycles

  Example 3 (dH=2): 8 total 7-cycles
    2 internal arcs: 6 cycles
    3 internal arcs: 2 cycles
  After reversal: 9 total 7-cycles
    2 internal arcs: 6 cycles
    3 internal arcs: 3 cycles

======================================================================
PART 8: THE EXACT MECHANISM — WHICH INTERNAL ARC CONFIGURATIONS SURVIVE?
======================================================================

Possible internal arc counts in a 7-cycle with 4 subset + 3 external vertices:
  Distribution of 3 ext in 4 gaps -> internal arcs:
  (3,0,0,0) -> 3 internal arcs
  (2,1,0,0) -> 2 internal arcs
  (1,1,1,0) -> 1 internal arc
  (cannot fill all 4 gaps with only 3 ext vertices)

  So internal arc count is in {1, 2, 3}.
  Reversal flips all internal arcs.
  A cycle SURVIVES reversal iff ALL its internal arcs are in BOTH directions
  in the original tournament (impossible for tournament: each arc has one direction).
  So NO cycle survives the reversal in its original form.
  Instead, cycles map to OTHER potential cycles.

  The delta_c7 = c7(B) - c7(A) counts the NET change in valid 7-cycles.

Verifying with concrete example:
  Tournament A: 9 7-cycles, B: 8 7-cycles
  Of A's 9 cycles: 0 survive in B, 9 lost
  Gained in B: 8
  Net: -1 = delta_c7

